\newlabel{tab:per-task-md}{{16}{21}{Per-task judge-keep outcome for the 8B markdown student on the 18-task hard held-out suite. $\checkmark $ = judge-kept; $\cdot $ = judge-rejected.\relax }{table.caption.59}{}}
\newlabel{tab:per-task-md@cref}{{[table][16][2147483647]16}{[1][18][]21}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {17}{\ignorespaces Single-shot vs.\ reviewed quality across six modalities, Claude Sonnet 4. Means and standard deviations are computed across three independent on-policy runs (per-run means, then aggregated). Code is binary pass-rate; other modalities are continuous in $[0,1]$. $p$-values: one-sided paired sign test on per-task means. \textbf  {Bold} marks rows where the lift clears $p < 0.05$. Code is scored by execution (\texttt  {pytest}); video by a native full-video rubric (Gemini\nobreakspace  {}3.1\nobreakspace  {}Pro judging the whole rendered clip); the four visual/factual rows use a holistic screenshot judge and serve only as a cross-modal overview. \emph  {This table is historical and is superseded for the visual modalities by the grounded measurements of \Cref  {sec:grounded_eval}}: under the deterministic DOM-geometry instrument (\Cref  {tab:geometric}) the figure, slide, web, and animation effects are large and significant, whereas the holistic-judge numbers here cannot see the geometric defects and therefore mis-state them. The visual rows here also use the earlier, smaller task sets ($15$ web and $15$ animation tasks, $20$ generic slides), not the hardened suites of \Cref  {tab:geometric} ($20$/$20$/$12$ real-paper); this is why the per-modality $N$ differs between the two tables. The deep-research and video rows also use \emph  {different} instruments than \Cref  {sec:grounded_eval}: research here is the old holistic judge ($0.63\to 0.69$) rather than the search-grounded factual rubric (single-shot $0.982$), so the large numeric gap is an instrument change, not a contradiction; video uses the same Gemini-native rubric in both places ($0.70\to 0.74$).\relax }}{21}{table.caption.60}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:harness-headline}{{17}{21}{Single-shot vs.\ reviewed quality across six modalities, Claude Sonnet 4. Means and standard deviations are computed across three independent on-policy runs (per-run means, then aggregated). Code is binary pass-rate; other modalities are continuous in $[0,1]$. $p$-values: one-sided paired sign test on per-task means. \textbf {Bold} marks rows where the lift clears $p < 0.05$. Code is scored by execution (\texttt {pytest}); video by a native full-video rubric (Gemini~3.1~Pro judging the whole rendered clip); the four visual/factual rows use a holistic screenshot judge and serve only as a cross-modal overview. \emph {This table is historical and is superseded for the visual modalities by the grounded measurements of \Cref {sec:grounded_eval}}: under the deterministic DOM-geometry instrument (\Cref {tab:geometric}) the figure, slide, web, and animation effects are large and significant, whereas the holistic-judge numbers here cannot see the geometric defects and therefore mis-state them. The visual rows here also use the earlier, smaller task sets ($15$ web and $15$ animation tasks, $20$ generic slides), not the hardened suites of \Cref {tab:geometric} ($20$/$20$/$12$ real-paper); this is why the per-modality $N$ differs between the two tables. The deep-research and video rows also use \emph {different} instruments than \Cref {sec:grounded_eval}: research here is the old holistic judge ($0.63\to 0.69$) rather than the search-grounded factual rubric (single-shot $0.982$), so the large numeric gap is an instrument change, not a contradiction; video uses the same Gemini-native rubric in both places ($0.70\to 0.74$).\relax }{table.caption.60}{}}
\newlabel{tab:harness-headline@cref}{{[table][17][2147483647]17}{[1][18][]21}}
